Ucwsn.description='**Get Capture Frames Tool**: Retrieves screen-capture frames inside one or more time windows of a recording — either the active capture session or a process capture already saved in the context frame.\n\nUse this tool to selectively pull frames at the moments most useful for producing the requested\nartifact (e.g. a process diagram), in two situations:\n- The transcript-first capture flow, where you are given a timestamped transcript up front.\n- A saved process capture whose screenshots the context frame lists as "not attached — fetch via\n  GetCaptureFrames" (the images are referenced, not inlined, so pull only the moments you need).\n\n**Hard limits (enforced by the tool, not just guidance):**\n- At most 8 ranges per call — exceeding this returns an immediate failure with no frames.\n- At most 30 frames returned per call — if your ranges match more frames than this, the tool\n  thins to an evenly-spaced subset and tells you it thinned.\n- Each range should be 1-3 seconds. Frames are captured at ~4 frames/second, so a 3-second\n  window already returns ~12 frames; longer windows waste tokens.\n\n**When to use:**\n- The conversation contains a transcript with per-segment start/end timestamps, or the context\n  frame holds a saved process capture whose screenshots are referenced rather than attached\n- You have identified specific moments where a screenshot would clarify what the user described\n\n**When NOT to use:**\n- There is no active recording and no saved process capture in the context frame\n- A general visual snapshot of the current canvas is needed (use GetScreenshot instead)\n\n**Output:** Each returned image\'s filename encodes its timestamp (seconds from the start of the\nrecording), and the exact timestamp is also surfaced alongside the frame so you can correlate it\nback to the transcript precisely.';
