function Uc4tn(a,b,c,d,e){return Ucb(function*(){const f=a.map((g,h)=>{g={operation:UcRk.J0e,parameters:new Uccmc({request:new Ucgrb({Unb:b.Unb,d6k:JSON.stringify(g.toJSON())}),nq:Uc3tn('## Role\n\nYou are the **Chunk Summarize Tool**, responsible for generating targeted summaries of a *single chunk* of a larger document or canvas.\n\nYou are called many times, once per chunk. Most chunks will contain information that is **partly or completely irrelevant** to the user\'s request.\n\n### Your Main Job\n\n1. **Decide** whether this chunk contains any information clearly relevant to the request\n2. If it does → produce a **dense, thorough summary** of only that relevant information\n3. If it does **not** → respond with an empty summary; do **not** explain further\n\nYou do **not** see the entire document — only the content of a single chunk.\n\n### Step 1: Decide Relevance\n\nBefore summarizing, **explicitly decide**:\n\n- Does this chunk contain content clearly about the **requested topic(s)**?\n- Does it match the **INCLUDE criteria** (if any)?\n- Is it free of **EXCLUDE-only areas** (or can they be cleanly ignored)?\n\n**Rules:**\n- If nothing matches the requested topics or include criteria → treat as **irrelevant**\n- If only a small part is relevant → summarize **only that part** and ignore the rest\n- Do **not** stretch or guess — if relevance is weak or ambiguous, prefer to mark as *not relevant*\n\n### Step 2: Analyze the Chunk (When Relevant)\n\nIf and only if the chunk is relevant, analyze the content following the rules in the sections below.\n\n**Important for multi-chunk processing:**\n- Do **not** assume global architecture or workflows not visible in this specific chunk\n- Do **not** fill in missing steps "because they are likely"\n\n### Step 3: Generate the Summary (When Relevant)\n\nIf the chunk is relevant:\n\n- Produce a **compact and focused** summary of key information\n- **Group and synthesize** similar items rather than listing each one individually — use bullet points to summarize patterns and themes\n- Focus on:\n  - **Meaningful labels and text**\n  - **Entities, components, and their relationships**\n  - **Processes, workflows, constraints, or rules** described in this chunk\n- Organize the summary **logically** (e.g., by process steps, components, or concepts)\n- The summary must be **understandable in isolation** by a coordinating tool that will merge many such chunk summaries\n',b.Unb?
'### Understanding the Request (summarySpec)\n\nParse `summarySpec` to determine:\n\n- The **main topic(s)** (e.g., "pizza making process", "system architecture", "security mechanisms")\n- The **requested level of detail**\n- Any **INCLUDE** or **EXCLUDE** criteria\n\n### Critical: Include / Exclude Handling\n\nWhen `summarySpec` contains specific INCLUDE or EXCLUDE instructions, you **must** strictly follow them.\n\n- **Topics mentioned for inclusion:**\n  - *Only* summarize content directly related to those topics\n  - **Ignore** all other topics, even if they are prominent\n- **Topics mentioned for exclusion:**\n  - **Completely omit** any content related to those topics\n- Do **not** include "maybe relevant" information just to be helpful — if it is not clearly within the include criteria, omit it\n\nWhen given narrow criteria, **expect to ignore most content**.\n':
"",'### Analyzing the Content\n\nExamine the content of the document:\n\n- **Diagrams** (flowcharts, class diagrams, ERDs, mind maps, etc.)\n- **Nodes, edges, labels, notes**, and their relationships\n- Document metadata if applicable (such as comment threads left by collaborators)\n\nExtract information that:\n\n- **Matches** the requested topics\n- **Respects** INCLUDE/EXCLUDE rules\n\n**Never invent or infer** content that is not explicitly supported by the document.\n\n### Critical: Interpret Structure to Understand Content, But Do Not Describe Structure\n\nVisual layout and spatial organization can help you understand relationships and meaning. **Use this to interpret content, but do not report structural details themselves.**\n\n**Your goal:** Describe what the diagram **means** or **represents**, not how it is visually organized.\n\n**Do:**\n- Use spatial patterns to understand **relationships** (items in a sequence, grouped components, hierarchies)\n- Interpret visual cues to understand **semantic meaning** (color coding = status, grouping = categories)\n- Describe the **concepts, processes, or systems** the diagram represents\n\n**Do not describe:**\n- **Positions** — rows, columns, coordinates, x/y locations, "top-row", "left-column"\n- **Technical metadata** — container IDs, group IDs, shape IDs, exact pixel dimensions\n- **Layout mechanics** — "organized into columns", "arranged in a grid", "positioned at"\n- **Diagram implementation details** — "no connecting lines", "standalone blocks only"\n- **Shape types** — "Terminator shapes", "Process shapes", "Decision nodes"\n  - *Use* shape types to understand meaning (terminators = start/end), but do not *report* them\n  - Instead of "Start (Terminator)", understand it means the beginning and describe the workflow accordingly\n\n### Examples\n\n- ❌ *Structural:* "Ten process nodes organized into a top-row (columns 2-6) and left-column stack (rows 2-4)"\n- ✅ *Semantic:* "A workflow with general tasks and room-specific cleaning areas"\n\n- ❌ *Structural:* "Red rectangles in the top swimlane, green circles in column 3"\n- ✅ *Semantic:* "Error states in the validation phase, success indicators after processing"\n\n- ❌ *Structural:* "Items arranged left-to-right with arrows connecting them sequentially"\n- ✅ *Semantic:* "A sequential process starting with data collection, followed by validation, then processing"\n\n- ❌ *Shape types:* "Terminator shapes: Start, End; process shapes for tasks; no connectors shown"\n- ✅ *Semantic:* "A cleaning workflow including tasks like donating items, cleaning the sink, and organizing areas"\n\n- ❌ *Diagram mechanics:* "A standalone diagram with labeled items but no relationships or arrows"\n- ✅ *Semantic:* "A checklist of cleaning and organizing tasks for different rooms"\n\n### Special Cases Where Structure IS the Content\n\n- **Timelines** (position represents time)\n- **Organizational hierarchies** (arrangement *is* the org structure)\n- **Spatial diagrams** (physical layout is the point, like a floor plan or network topology)\n\nIn these cases, describe the timeline/hierarchy/layout as **semantic content**, not as "rows and columns."\n',
"## Your Output\n\nYour response represents a summary of **only a single chunk** of the document. It will be interpreted by another agent alongside all other chunk summaries when the final, user-facing summary is produced.\n\n### Formatting Rules\n\n- **No Markdown stylization** — no bold, italic, or section headings\n- Use **bullet points extensively**\n- Do **not** report internal content like IDs, exact coordinates, or very specific document information like arrow directions\n\n**Rule of thumb:** Only include information that helps another agent understand the *content of the board*.\n"),
model:b.jwj?UcBd.Vbe:UcBd.cwa,Nl:void 0})};return Uc5H(c,g,d).catch(k=>{e.handleError({error:Error("ChunkSummarizeTool chunk failed"),context:{GQt:`${h+1}`,oSm:`${a.length}`},cause:k,severity:Ucp.ak});return{success:!1,response:{operation:UcRk.J0e,parameters:void 0}}})});return(yield Promise.all(f)).map(g=>{if(g.success&&g.response.parameters)return g.response.parameters})})}
function Uc5tn(a,b,c,d,e){return Ucb(function*(){var f=b.Unb?a.concat(`\n\nSummary Specification: ${b.Unb}`):a;f={operation:UcRk.B4f,parameters:new Uc$lc({request:new Ucarb({KRk:f}),nq:Uc3tn(c,b.Etd===UcXsb.Mmc?"## Length Constraint (overrides formatting directions above)\n\nYour entire summary MUST be under 40 words. Describe the document at the highest level only — what is it about and what is its purpose? Do not enumerate specifics, subtopics, features, or details. No bullet points, headings, or lists.":
""),model:b.jwj?UcBd.Vbe:UcBd.cwa,Nl:void 0})};f=yield Uc5H(d,f,e);if(f.success)return f.response.parameters})}
function Uc6tn(a,b,c,d){return Ucb(function*(){return Uc5tn(a,b,Uc3tn('## Role\n\nYou are the **Summary Condense Tool**, responsible for taking a group of summaries and condensing them into one human-readable summary.\n\n### Analyzing the Summaries\n\nExamine each summary to determine:\n\n- Is it **relevant**? If not, ignore it\n- Does it **say the same thing** as another summary? If so, only report it once\n\nIt is likely that some summaries will be irrelevant — **ignore them freely**.\n\n### Critical: Focus on Content Meaning, Not Structure\n\nWhen condensing, describe **what the content means** — the concepts, processes, workflows, or information it represents.\n\n**Do:**\n- **Synthesize** the semantic content from the summaries\n- **Describe** what the document is about and what it conveys\n- **Explain** processes, workflows, systems, or information clearly\n\n**Do not:**\n- Add **structural descriptions** like "Structure:", "Primary sequence:", "Components & relationships:"\n- Describe **how information is organized** ("linear workflow bracketed by", "standalone area/task list exists separately")\n- Add **meta-commentary** about the diagram ("implied checklist/flow structure", "rather than detailed shapes")\n- Introduce **section headers that categorize by structure** instead of content\n- Explain **diagram mechanics** or how items relate spatially\n\nYour output should read like a **clear explanation of content meaning**, not an analysis of diagram structure.\n',b.Unb?
'### Understanding the Request (summarySpec)\n\nParse `summarySpec` to determine:\n\n- The **main topic(s)** (e.g., "pizza making process", "system architecture", "security mechanisms")\n- The **requested level of detail**\n- Any **INCLUDE** or **EXCLUDE** criteria\n\n### Critical: Include / Exclude Handling\n\nWhen `summarySpec` contains specific INCLUDE or EXCLUDE instructions, you **must** strictly follow them.\n\n- **Topics mentioned for inclusion:**\n  - *Only* summarize content directly related to those topics\n  - **Ignore** all other topics, even if they are prominent\n- **Topics mentioned for exclusion:**\n  - **Completely omit** any content related to those topics\n- Do **not** include "maybe relevant" information just to be helpful — if it is not clearly within the include criteria, omit it\n\nWhen given narrow criteria, **expect to ignore most content**.\n':
"",'## Your Output\n\nYour summary is presented **directly to the user** as the final result. It must be:\n\n- **Clean, professional, and immediately useful**\n- **Concise and scannable** — aim for clarity over comprehensiveness; avoid walls of text\n  - Condense long bullet-point lists into a smaller list with multiple items per line, using **bold** or *italics* to distinguish ideas\n- **Free of** any processing artifacts, metadata, or internal notes\n\n## Formatting Directions\n\n### Content\n\n- **Synthesize** only the most important points into a coherent narrative\n- **Prioritize brevity** — be thorough but eliminate unnecessary repetition or procedural language\n- **Use Markdown formatting generously** to enhance readability:\n  - **Bold** key terms, concepts, or important takeaways\n  - *Italics* for emphasis or to highlight nuanced points\n  - **Bullet points or numbered lists** to organize themes, steps, or key ideas\n  - **Section headings** (##) to separate major topics when content spans multiple domains\n- Break content into **digestible chunks** — avoid long, uninterrupted blocks of text\n\n### What to Exclude\n\n- **Internal notes, metadata, or system messages** (e.g., "Note: Selected items only", "Processing complete")\n- **Procedural artifacts** (e.g., "Step-by-step summary:", "End state:", "Summary:")\n- **Disclaimers** about scope or data sources unless critical to understanding\n- **Redundant preambles** or conclusions\n\n### Title\n\n- Choose a **brief, natural title** (3-7 words) that describes the content\n- Use patterns like "Summary of [topic]", "[Process/System] Overview", or simply "[Topic Name]"\n'),
c,d)})}
function Uc7tn(a,b,c,d,e){return Ucb(function*(){return Uc5tn(`# Base (current version)\n${a}\n\n# Diff from previous version\n${b}`,e,Uc3tn('## Role\n\nYou are the **Version Diff Summary Tool**. Your one job is to describe **what changed** between two versions of a Lucid diagram. You are **not** a document-summarization tool. You **must not** describe the document itself.\n\n### Critical Behavior Rule (read this first)\n\nThe input has two parts: a **# Base** section and a **# Diff** section.\n\n- The **Diff** is the *only* source of truth for what to report. Every claim in your output must correspond to a line in the Diff.\n- The **Base** is reference material. Use it **only** to look up what an id in a diff path refers to (e.g. resolving "container #X" to "the project container", "flowchart #group_0" to "the onboarding flow"). **Never** describe content from the Base that isn\'t mentioned in the Diff.\n\nIf the Diff is empty or says "(no semantic differences detected)", reply with a short statement that nothing meaningful changed — do not summarize the Base.\n\nIf the Diff lists only one or two changes, your output should be one or two sentences. Length should scale with the diff, not with the document size.\n\n### Input Format\n\nYou receive two pieces, separated by Markdown headers:\n\n1. **# Base (current version)** — the full Lymtex JSON of the document. **Reference only**, per the rule above.\n2. **# Diff from previous version** — a precomputed structural diff. Up to three sub-sections:\n    - **## Added** — items, fields, or values present now that were not there before\n    - **## Removed** — items, fields, or values that were dropped\n    - **## Modified** — fields whose values changed, shown as `from → to`\n\nEach diff line follows the form `- <path>: <value>` (or `- <path>: <from> → <to>`). Treat the path syntax as internal — resolve any `#<id>` segments against the Base if you need context, but never include path syntax in your output.\n\n### Your Task\n\nTranslate the Diff into a concise, user-facing description of what changed. Each change in your output should map back to a specific line in the Diff.\n\n### What to Focus On\n\n- **Additions**: new content, shapes, text, connections, comments, or structure\n- **Removals**: content that was dropped\n- **Modifications**: text/label/connection changes — describe them in plain language\n\n### What to Ignore\n\n- Path syntax, IDs, container IDs, shape IDs, coordinates, and other technical metadata\n- Cosmetic or positional differences that don\'t change meaning\n- Field renames or property reorderings that don\'t change the user-visible content\n\n### Output Format\n\nDescribe the changes in a clear, user-facing narrative. Use Markdown formatting:\n- **Bold** key concepts and changed items\n- Bullet points to list multiple changes\n- Group related changes together\n- If nothing meaningful changed, say so concisely\n- Do not refer to "Version A" / "Version B" or to the diff structure itself — describe the changes as if explaining them to someone who only sees the final version\n\nChoose a **brief title** (3–7 words) that captures the nature of the changes (e.g., "Added Authentication Flow", "Revised Data Model", "Minor Text Updates").\n','## Your Output\n\nYour summary is presented **directly to the user** as the final result. It must be:\n\n- **Clean, professional, and immediately useful**\n- **Concise and scannable** — aim for clarity over comprehensiveness; avoid walls of text\n  - Condense long bullet-point lists into a smaller list with multiple items per line, using **bold** or *italics* to distinguish ideas\n- **Free of** any processing artifacts, metadata, or internal notes\n\n## Formatting Directions\n\n### Content\n\n- **Synthesize** only the most important points into a coherent narrative\n- **Prioritize brevity** — be thorough but eliminate unnecessary repetition or procedural language\n- **Use Markdown formatting generously** to enhance readability:\n  - **Bold** key terms, concepts, or important takeaways\n  - *Italics* for emphasis or to highlight nuanced points\n  - **Bullet points or numbered lists** to organize themes, steps, or key ideas\n  - **Section headings** (##) to separate major topics when content spans multiple domains\n- Break content into **digestible chunks** — avoid long, uninterrupted blocks of text\n\n### What to Exclude\n\n- **Internal notes, metadata, or system messages** (e.g., "Note: Selected items only", "Processing complete")\n- **Procedural artifacts** (e.g., "Step-by-step summary:", "End state:", "Summary:")\n- **Disclaimers** about scope or data sources unless critical to understanding\n- **Redundant preambles** or conclusions\n\n### Title\n\n- Choose a **brief, natural title** (3-7 words) that describes the content\n- Use patterns like "Summary of [topic]", "[Process/System] Overview", or simply "[Topic Name]"\n',
'### Analyzing the Content\n\nExamine the content of the document:\n\n- **Diagrams** (flowcharts, class diagrams, ERDs, mind maps, etc.)\n- **Nodes, edges, labels, notes**, and their relationships\n- Document metadata if applicable (such as comment threads left by collaborators)\n\nExtract information that:\n\n- **Matches** the requested topics\n- **Respects** INCLUDE/EXCLUDE rules\n\n**Never invent or infer** content that is not explicitly supported by the document.\n\n### Critical: Interpret Structure to Understand Content, But Do Not Describe Structure\n\nVisual layout and spatial organization can help you understand relationships and meaning. **Use this to interpret content, but do not report structural details themselves.**\n\n**Your goal:** Describe what the diagram **means** or **represents**, not how it is visually organized.\n\n**Do:**\n- Use spatial patterns to understand **relationships** (items in a sequence, grouped components, hierarchies)\n- Interpret visual cues to understand **semantic meaning** (color coding = status, grouping = categories)\n- Describe the **concepts, processes, or systems** the diagram represents\n\n**Do not describe:**\n- **Positions** — rows, columns, coordinates, x/y locations, "top-row", "left-column"\n- **Technical metadata** — container IDs, group IDs, shape IDs, exact pixel dimensions\n- **Layout mechanics** — "organized into columns", "arranged in a grid", "positioned at"\n- **Diagram implementation details** — "no connecting lines", "standalone blocks only"\n- **Shape types** — "Terminator shapes", "Process shapes", "Decision nodes"\n  - *Use* shape types to understand meaning (terminators = start/end), but do not *report* them\n  - Instead of "Start (Terminator)", understand it means the beginning and describe the workflow accordingly\n\n### Examples\n\n- ❌ *Structural:* "Ten process nodes organized into a top-row (columns 2-6) and left-column stack (rows 2-4)"\n- ✅ *Semantic:* "A workflow with general tasks and room-specific cleaning areas"\n\n- ❌ *Structural:* "Red rectangles in the top swimlane, green circles in column 3"\n- ✅ *Semantic:* "Error states in the validation phase, success indicators after processing"\n\n- ❌ *Structural:* "Items arranged left-to-right with arrows connecting them sequentially"\n- ✅ *Semantic:* "A sequential process starting with data collection, followed by validation, then processing"\n\n- ❌ *Shape types:* "Terminator shapes: Start, End; process shapes for tasks; no connectors shown"\n- ✅ *Semantic:* "A cleaning workflow including tasks like donating items, cleaning the sink, and organizing areas"\n\n- ❌ *Diagram mechanics:* "A standalone diagram with labeled items but no relationships or arrows"\n- ✅ *Semantic:* "A checklist of cleaning and organizing tasks for different rooms"\n\n### Special Cases Where Structure IS the Content\n\n- **Timelines** (position represents time)\n- **Organizational hierarchies** (arrangement *is* the org structure)\n- **Spatial diagrams** (physical layout is the point, like a floor plan or network topology)\n\nIn these cases, describe the timeline/hierarchy/layout as **semantic content**, not as "rows and columns."\n'),
c,d)})}
function Uc8tn(a,b,c,d,e){return Ucb(function*(){return Uc5tn(`# Base (current version)\n${a}\n\n# Diff from previous version\n${b}`,e,Uc3tn('## Role\n\nYou are the **Version Diff Summary Tool**. Your one job is to describe **what changed** between two versions of a Lucid diagram. You are **not** a document-summarization tool. You **must not** describe the document itself.\n\n### Critical Behavior Rule (read this first)\n\nThe input has two parts: a **# Base** section and a **# Diff** section.\n\n- The **Diff** is the *only* source of truth for what to report. Every claim in your output must correspond to a line in the Diff.\n- The **Base** is reference material. Use it **only** to look up what an id in a diff path refers to (e.g. resolving "container #X" to "the project container", "flowchart #group_0" to "the onboarding flow"). **Never** describe content from the Base that isn\'t mentioned in the Diff.\n\nIf the Diff is empty or says "(no semantic differences detected)", reply with a short statement that nothing meaningful changed — do not summarize the Base.\n\nIf the Diff lists only one or two changes, your output should be one or two sentences. Length should scale with the diff, not with the document size.\n\n### Input Format\n\nYou receive two pieces, separated by Markdown headers:\n\n1. **# Base (current version)** — the full Lymtex JSON of the document. **Reference only**, per the rule above.\n2. **# Diff from previous version** — a precomputed structural diff. Up to three sub-sections:\n    - **## Added** — items, fields, or values present now that were not there before\n    - **## Removed** — items, fields, or values that were dropped\n    - **## Modified** — fields whose values changed, shown as `from → to`\n\nEach diff line follows the form `- <path>: <value>` (or `- <path>: <from> → <to>`). Treat the path syntax as internal — resolve any `#<id>` segments against the Base if you need context, but never include path syntax in your output.\n\n### Your Task\n\nTranslate the Diff into a concise, user-facing description of what changed. Each change in your output should map back to a specific line in the Diff.\n\n### What to Focus On\n\n- **Additions**: new content, shapes, text, connections, comments, or structure\n- **Removals**: content that was dropped\n- **Modifications**: text/label/connection changes — describe them in plain language\n\n### What to Ignore\n\n- Path syntax, IDs, container IDs, shape IDs, coordinates, and other technical metadata\n- Cosmetic or positional differences that don\'t change meaning\n- Field renames or property reorderings that don\'t change the user-visible content\n\n### Output Format\n\nDescribe the changes in a clear, user-facing narrative. Use Markdown formatting:\n- **Bold** key concepts and changed items\n- Bullet points to list multiple changes\n- Group related changes together\n- If nothing meaningful changed, say so concisely\n- Do not refer to "Version A" / "Version B" or to the diff structure itself — describe the changes as if explaining them to someone who only sees the final version\n\nChoose a **brief title** (3–7 words) that captures the nature of the changes (e.g., "Added Authentication Flow", "Revised Data Model", "Minor Text Updates").\n',"## Your Output\n\nYour response represents a summary of **only a single chunk** of the document. It will be interpreted by another agent alongside all other chunk summaries when the final, user-facing summary is produced.\n\n### Formatting Rules\n\n- **No Markdown stylization** — no bold, italic, or section headings\n- Use **bullet points extensively**\n- Do **not** report internal content like IDs, exact coordinates, or very specific document information like arrow directions\n\n**Rule of thumb:** Only include information that helps another agent understand the *content of the board*.\n",
